doc.ContractDescription: THE PLANCK SATELLITE HAS PRODUCED A MAP OF SO- CALLED "ANOMALOUS MICROWAVE EMISSION (AME)," A SIGNATURE THAT PEAKS IN THE MICROWAVE, BUT SPECTRALLY CANNOT BE ASSOCIATED WITH KNOWN SOURCES OF DIFFUSE EMISSION. THE LEADING IDEA IS THAT THIS EMISSION IS DUE TO TINY RAPIDLY SPINNING DUST GRAINS. IN THIS CASE, LARGE MOLECULES CALLED "POLYCYCLIC AROMATIC HYDROCARBONS (PAH)" COULD LIKELY BE RESPONSIBLE. THESE PARTICLES EMIT IN THE NEAR INFRARED. THE WISE SATELLITE HAS MAPPED THE SKY IN THE NEAR-INFRARED, SO BY SPATIALLY COMPARING THE PLANCK AND WISE MAPS, WE CAN TEST THE PHYSICS OF THE AME.
